The inverse of a $two \times two$ matrix $\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix}$ is given by
\[\frac{one}{ad - bc} \begin{pmatrix} d & -b \\ -c & a \end{pmatrix}.\]In this case, $ad - bc = (nine)(-twelve) - (eighteen)(-six) = zero,$ so the inverse does not exist.
Therefore, the inverse is the zero matrix $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} zero & zero \\ zero & zero \end{pmatrix}}.$The answer is: \begin{pmatrix}zero&zero\zero&zero\end{pmatrix}

The absolute value of a complex number $a+bi$ is given by $\sqrt{a^two+b^two}$.
So, the absolute value of $\frac{five}{six}+2i$ is $\sqrt{\left(\frac{five}{six}\right)^two+(two)^two}=\sqrt{\frac{twenty-five}{thirty-six}+four}=\sqrt{\frac{twenty-five+one hundred and forty-four}{thirty-six}}=\sqrt{\frac{one hundred and sixty-nine}{thirty-six}}=\frac{thirteen}{six}$.
Therefore, $\left|\frac{five}{six}+2i\right|=\boxed{\frac{thirteen}{six}}$. The answer is: \frac{thirteen}{six}

