If Eugene runs at a rate of four miles per hour, then Brianna runs at a rate of $\frac{two}{three} \cdot four = \frac{eight}{three}$ miles per hour.
Similarly, Katie runs at a rate of $\frac{seven}{five} \cdot \frac{eight}{three} = \frac{fifty-six}{fifteen}$ miles per hour.
Therefore, Katie runs at a speed of $\boxed{\frac{fifty-six}{fifteen}}$ miles per hour.The answer is: \frac{fifty-six}{fifteen}

We can line up the decimal points and then add the numbers as usual:
\[
\begin{array}{@{}c@{\;}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& & & & & four & . & three & & & \\
& & + & & & three & . & eight & eight & & \\
\cline{two-ten}
& & & & & eight & . & one & eight & & \\
\end{array}
\]
So, $four point three + three point eight eight = \boxed{eight point one eight}$.The answer is: eight point one eight

